<center>
  &nbsp;
</center>
<a name="Leslie"></a><b>Leslie, Alan M. The necessity of illusion: Perception 
and thought in infancy</b>. <a href="#top">Weiskrantz (1988)</a>, pp. 185-210. 
<p>
Abstract: (from the chapter) discuss three examples of the way in which events 
are understood early in development... infants perceive a specifically causal 
property of a simple event; infants show a thoughtful reaction to a more complex 
causal situation; full-blown counterfactual causal reasoning is involved at the 
start of childhood... causal inference and metarepresentation. 
